revision.text:
{{Use dmy dates|date=July 2013}} [[File:Dublin St. Patrick's Cathedral North Transept Window King Cormac of Cashel Detail Irish Royal Regiment 2012 09 26.jpg|thumb|300px|Memorial window from [[St Patrick's Cathedral, Dublin]] executed by An Túr Gloine.]] '''An Túr Gloine''' ({{IPA-ga|ənˠ ˈt̪ˠuːɾˠ ˈɡlˠɪnʲə|}}; [[Irish language|Irish]] for "The Glass Tower") was a [[cooperative]] [[studio]] for [[stained glass]] and ''[[opus sectile]]'' artists from 1903 until 1944,<ref name="Gordon Bowe BC">{{cite web|last1=Gordon Bowe|first1=Nicola|title=The Tower of Glass An Túr Gloine and the early 20th century stained glass revival in Ireland|url=http://www.buildingconservation.com/articles/towerofglass/towerofglass.htm|website=Building Conservation|accessdate=3 June 2015}}</ref> based in [[Dublin]], [[Republic of Ireland|Ireland]].
==History== An Túr Gloine was conceived of in late 1901 and established January 1903 at 24 Pembroke Street, [[Dublin]], [[Ireland]], on the site of two former tennis courts.It was active throughout the first half of the 20th century. Affiliated artists included [[Michael Healy (artist)|Michael Healy]], [[Evie Hone]], [[Beatrice Elvery]], [[Wilhelmina Geddes]], [[Harry Clarke]], [[Catherine Amelia O’Brien|Catherine O'Brien]], [[Kathleen Quigly]], and founder [[Sarah Purser]].<ref name="Gordon Bowe BC" /> The original impetus for the project, spurred by the Irish cultural activist [[Edward Martyn]], was the building of the [[Roman Catholic]] cathedral in [[Loughrea]], [[County Galway]], which was to become St. Brendan's.<ref>Martin Wallace, ''100 Irish Lives'' (Rowman & Littlefield, 1983), p. 122 [https://books.google.com/books?id=lbv5ZSsoVHMC&pg=PA122&dq=%22An+Tur+Gloine%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3 online.]</ref> Purser and Martyn hoped to provide an alternative to the commercial stained glass imported from England and Germany for Irish churches and other architectural projects.<ref>Entry on stained glass, ''The Blackwell Companion to Modern Irish Culture'', edited by W.J. McCormack (Wiley-Blackwell, 2001), p. 542 [https://books.google.com/books?id=ANgdh-3cMowC&pg=PA542&dq=%22An+Tur+Gloine%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3 online.]</ref> Purser's knowledge of French and English medieval glass, together with her social connections and organizational skills, were crucial to the success of the cooperative.<ref name="Gordon Bowe BC" />
A writer for ''[[Studio Magazine|The Studio]]'', a magazine of [[fine art|fine]] and [[applied art]], called the recently formed An Túr Gloine "perhaps the most noteworthy example of the newly awakened desire to foster Irish genius," describing it as "at once a craft school, where instruction in every detail connected with the designing and production of stained glass is given to the workers, and a factory from which some beautiful work has already appeared." The writer also extolled the economic benefits of an Irish glass industry to supply churches.<ref>E.D. (initials only), ''The Studio'' 33 (15 October 1904), pp. 260 and 262 [https://books.google.com/books?id=7fwEAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA4-PA260&dq=%22foster+Irish+artistic%22+intitle:Studio&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=0 online.]</ref> The studio is regarded as part of the [[Arts and Crafts Movement]],<ref name="online">Ellen Mary Easton McLeod, ''In Good Hands: The Women of the Canadian Handicrafts Guild'' (McGill-Queen's Press, 1999), pp. 55 and 68 (note 24) [https://books.google.com/books?id=npppnhZSmIIC&pg=PA68&dq=ottawa+window+intitle:in+intitle:good+intitle:hands&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&as_brr=0 online.]</ref> but was infused also with the contemporary spirit of [[Celtic Revival|Irish revivalism]]<ref>Characterized, perhaps dismissively, as "[[Romanticism|romantic]] [[nationalism|nationalist]] fervour" in ''The Blackwell Companion to Modern Irish Culture'', p. 542.</ref> and drew on the [[Celtic art#Ireland|artistic tradition of Celtic]] [[Illuminated manuscript|manuscript illumination]]. Ireland became an internationally renowned center of stained-glass art at this time, to a large extent as a result of An Túr Gloine.<ref>Terence Brown, ''Ireland: A Social and Cultural History, 1922 to the Present'' (Cornell University Press, 1985), p. 78 [https://books.google.com/books?id=1xwLMi6RaQcC&pg=PA78&dq=%22An+Tur+Gloine%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3 online]; ''The Blackwell Companion to Modern Irish Culture'', p. 542.</ref> The studio was run by Purser until 1940, and she was succeeded by Catherine O'Brien who ran it until 1944.<ref name="Gordon Bowe BC" /> After which time O'Brien bought the studio and leased a large section of it to [[Patrick Pollen]].<ref name=Doyle>{{cite book|last1=Doyle|first1=Carmel|editor1-last=McGuire|editor1-first=James|editor2-last=Quinn|editor2-first=James|title=Dictionary of Irish Biography|date=2009|publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge|chapter=O'Brien, Catherine Amelia}}</ref>
==Relation to literary culture== {{Expand section|date=December 2009}} A commission for An Túr Gloine occasioned an outburst of criticism in [[Samhain magazine|''Samhain'' magazine]] from the [[Irish poetry|Irish poet]] [[W.B. Yeats]] on how the "[[Bourgeois personality|bourgeois mind]] is never sincere in the arts":
{{cquote|[[Galway]] [[convent]] a little time ago refused a fine design for stained glass, sent from Miss Sarah Purser's studio, because of the personal life in the faces and in the [[Attitude (art)|attitudes]], which seemed to them ugly, perhaps even impious. They sent to Miss Purser an insipid German [[Chromolithography|chromo-lithograph]], full of faces without expression or dignity, and gestures without personal distinction, and Miss Purser, doubtless because her enterprise was too new, too anxious for success, to reject any order, has carried out this ignoble design in glass of beautiful colour and quality.<ref>''The Collected Letters of W.B. Yeats'', edited by John Kelly and Ronald Schuchard (Oxford University Press, 2005), p. 259, note 2 [https://books.google.com/books?id=k-DdGwpJb_wC&pg=PA259&dq=%22An+Tur+Gloine%22&lr=&as_drrb_is=q&as_minm_is=0&as_miny_is=&as_maxm_is=0&as_maxy_is=&num=100&as_brr=3 online.]</ref>}}
